docs.abstract: I almost always side with protecting houses of worship. But there are limits.
docs.snippet: I almost always side with protecting houses of worship. But there are limits.
docs.lead_paragraph: Gov. Andrew Cuomo has imposed new restrictions on businesses, mass gatherings and places of worship in towns and New York City neighborhoods with high rates of coronavirus infections — some of which also have large populations of Orthodox and Hasidic Jews. An Orthodox advocacy group, Agudath Israel of America, has filed a federal lawsuit against the new regulations on the grounds that they violate the right to free exercise of religion.

headline.main: Do Cuomo’s New Covid Rules Discriminate Against Religion?

docs.abstract: Imagine how wide the ripples of impact can be when a woman of color is vice president.
docs.snippet: Imagine how wide the ripples of impact can be when a woman of color is vice president.
docs.lead_paragraph: I was on a hike in Garrison, N.Y., when I heard the news of Kamala Harris and Joe Biden’s victory. I felt elated. Then suddenly I felt this heat welling up from my chest into my throat and it burst out of me in tears I could not control. At first I didn’t even know why I was sobbing.

headline.main: Padma Lakshmi: Vice President-Elect Kamala Harris Moved Me to Tears
headline.print_headline: Kamala Harris Moved Me to Tears

docs.abstract: Actions taken by paramilitary groups in Michigan last year, emboldened by President Donald J. Trump, signaled a profound shift in Republican politics and a national crisis in the making.
docs.snippet: Actions taken by paramilitary groups in Michigan last year, emboldened by President Donald J. Trump, signaled a profound shift in Republican politics and a national crisis in the making.
docs.lead_paragraph: LANSING, Mich. — Dozens of heavily armed militiamen crowded into the Michigan Statehouse last April to protest a stay-at-home order by the Democratic governor to slow the pandemic. Chanting and stomping their feet, they halted legislative business, tried to force their way onto the floor and brandished rifles from the gallery over lawmakers below.

headline.main: ‘Its Own Domestic Army’: How the G.O.P. Allied Itself With Militants
headline.print_headline: G.O.P.’s Embrace of Michigan Militias Set Up Stark Political Shift

docs.abstract: The making of Sheila Pree Bright’s photo-mural of black women who had lost their sons gave a group of mothers a chance to tell their stories.
docs.snippet: The making of Sheila Pree Bright’s photo-mural of black women who had lost their sons gave a group of mothers a chance to tell their stories.
docs.lead_paragraph: The past informs the present in the work of Sheila Pree Bright, who has been photographing the Black Lives Matter movement since 2014. As an artist who draws connections between today’s young activists and their civil rights forebears, she seemed a natural choice to be among 11 socially conscious artists selected to create murals highlighting Atlanta’s past, present and future in time for the Super Bowl, when the city will be in the spotlight.

headline.main: From the Civil Rights Movement to Black Lives Matter: Honoring Black Mothers Who Lost Their Sons

docs.lead_paragraph: Natalie Pontius is an interior decorator, married with two children and a University of Georgia alumna. She was born and raised in Atlanta, but moved to the city’s exurbs with her family several years ago, drawn to the region’s quality of public education. In November, she’s voting for Donald Trump.
